{
  "text": "In healthy subjects, euglycemic hyperinsulinemia and carbohydrate-rich meals increase skeletal muscle blood flow through insulin receptor signaling and activation of endothelial nitric oxide synthase. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] This response leads to an increase in capillary blood volume (CBV) and a higher functional capillary surface area, which in turn facilitates insulin-mediated glucose uptake. [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] Insulin resistance (IR) and obesity limit the insulin-mediated expansion of CBV, which is thought to contribute to reduced glucose uptake. [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] Furthermore, we have demonstrated that inactivity, in the absence of obesity, reduces the CBV response to a glucose challenge and strongly correlates with the degree of IR. [CITATION_14] Vasoactive compounds other than nitric oxide are thought to participate in the metabolic regulation of CBV. Metabolism of arachadonic acid through cytochrome P-450 enzymes produce epoxyeicosatrienoic acids (EETs), a family of endothelial-derived vasodilators that can influence skeletal muscle blood flow.",
  "correct_citation": {
